Date: 14/8/1958
Source: Christchurch Star-Sun
Author:
Vol / Page: 13
Edition:
Quote:  The farming technique known as the `sacrifice' paddock, in which one paddock on a farm is heavily stocked during the winter to save pastures elsewhere on the farm for use by cattle after calving was criticised by the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in the Palmerston North Magistrates' Court today. ... in Dalefield's case it had been the stock rather than the paddock which had been `sacrificed'
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1982
Source: Collins Concise English Dictionary
Author:
Vol / Page: 1015
Edition:
Quote: <i>sacrifice paddock n. N.Z.</i> a grassed field which is allowed to be grazed completely, so that it can be cultivated and resown later.
Notes:  [nf. 1986 NZPOD; 1985 Collins NZ Compact Dict. 428]

Date: 9/9/2004
Source: Dominion Post
Author:
Vol / Page: C7
Edition:
Quote: His practice of putting his herd in a "sacrifice" paddock is common among dairy farmers. Rather than damage all his farm moving his herd around in the mud, he opts to sacrifice poorly performing paddocks and later cultivate and resow them with a crop followed by new grass when the weather improves.
